en/birth-child-raising-traditions-in-turkey/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/birth-child-raising-traditions-in-turkey/#webpage"},"image":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/birth-and-child-raising-traditions-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/birth-child-raising-traditions-in-turkey/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey, with its rich historical and cultural heritage, has a very diverse structure in terms of birth and child-rearing traditions. These traditions range from family structure to social norms, and each region has its own unique practices. In this article, we will provide a comprehensive guide to the traditions of childbirth and childrearing in Turkey, giving readers the opportunity to explore these cultural riches.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="birth-traditions-in-turkey-cultural-richnesses-and-practices">Birth Traditions in Turkey: Cultural Richnesses and Practices</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In Turkey, birth is an important part of families and society. The prenatal, birth and postnatal processes are enriched with various traditions and rituals.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="pre-natal-traditions">Pre-Natal Traditions</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Forty Flyover / Puerperal Visits</strong> It is believed that the mother and baby should not leave the house for 40 days after the birth. During this period, forty prayers are recited to protect the mother and baby, and maternity sherbet is served to visiting guests. At the end of the 40th day, a &#8220;fortying&#8221; ritual is performed with the baby; the baby is bathed, dressed in new clothes and rose petals are thrown into the water for fertility.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Belief of the Golden Wife and Prevention Methods</strong> In Anatolia, it is believed that a malevolent entity called &#8220;al wife&#8221; can harm puerperant mothers and newborn babies. With this belief: The Holy Quran is placed under the puerperant&#8217;s pillow, a red ribbon is hung in the room or an evil eye bead is placed on the mother and baby.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Postpartum Nutrition and Puerperal Sherbet</strong> Special foods are prepared for the postpartum mother to increase her milk and energize her. She is offered puerperal sherbet (a traditional drink made with cinnamon, cloves and sugar). He is encouraged to consume nutritious foods such as molasses, tahini, bulgur soup and nettle dishes.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="moment-of-birth">Moment of Birth</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In Turkey, the moment of birth is an important moment surrounded by deeply rooted beliefs and traditions. Families recite prayers to ensure a smooth and healthy birth, and take various precautions to ward off the evil eye. In some regions of Anatolia, soothing music or lullabies are played during childbirth to relax the mother and facilitate the process. These practices are passed down through generations, providing moral support and keeping cultural identity alive.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="postpartum-traditions-first-days-of-mothers-and-babies-in-turkey">Postpartum Traditions: First Days of Mothers and Babies in Turkey</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The postpartum period is a special time for mother and baby. Various traditions and celebrations are held during this period.</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Baby Mevlidi:</strong> After the birth, families usually organize a baby mevlidi. At this event, family and friends gather and prayers are said.</li>



<li><strong>Lohusa Sherbet:</strong> The mother is offered sherbet after the birth. This tradition is done to support the health of the mother.</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">You can also take a look at <a href="https://roadtostudy.com/en/wedding-traditions-events-in-turkey/" data-type="link" data-id="https://roadtostudy.com/en/wedding-traditions-events-in-turkey/">Wedding Traditions and Events in Turkey</a>.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="child-raising-methods-family-structures-and-traditions-in-turkey">Child Raising Methods: Family Structures and Traditions in Turkey</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Child rearing in Turkey varies depending on family structure and social norms. Families are generally loving and protective of their children.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="family-structure">Family Structure</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Extended Family:</strong> The extended family structure is common in Turkey. Children grow up with their parents, grandparents and other relatives. This gives children social skills.</li>



<li><strong>Mother-Father Role:</strong> Mothers usually take an active role in the education and care of children, while fathers are responsible for providing for the family.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="traditional-methods">Traditional Methods</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Education:</strong> Children are taught moral values, traditions and religion at an early age. This helps children to adapt to society.</li>



<li><strong>Social Interaction:</strong> Children grow up interacting socially with their peers. This helps them to improve their communication skills.</li>
</ul>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="mother-father-relationship-family-dynamics-in-child-raising-in-turkey">Mother-Father Relationship: Family Dynamics in Child Raising in Turkey</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The parental relationship plays a critical role in the child-rearing process. Dynamics within the family are a determining factor in children&#8217;s development in Turkey.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="contact-and-support">Contact and Support</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Open Communication:</strong> Families try to understand their children&#8217;s emotional needs by communicating openly with them. This makes it easier for children to express themselves.</li>



<li><strong>Supportive Environment:</strong> Families organize various activities to support their children&#8217;s education and personal development.</li>
</ul>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="modern-and-traditional-methods-finding-balance-in-child-raising-in-turkey">Modern and Traditional Methods: Finding Balance in Child Raising in Turkey</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Child rearing in Turkey involves a combination of modern and traditional methods. Families try to use these methods in a balanced way according to the needs of their children.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="training-methods">Training Methods</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Traditional Education:</strong> Families prioritize instilling basic values such as respect, responsibility and honesty in their children. Cultural heritage, such as respect for elders, hospitality and holiday traditions, is taught by living at home. At the same time, children&#8217;s academic success is highly valued; regular studying, homework tracking and school-family cooperation are encouraged.</li>



<li><strong>Modern Education:</strong> In recent years, private schools, technology integration and alternative education models have become more popular among families. Starting foreign language education, coding and robotics at an early age contributes to preparing children for the global world. This approach aims to develop both academic and social skills of children.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="social-activity-and-interaction">Social Activity and Interaction</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Traditional Events:</strong> Families direct their children to traditional activities such as folk dances, baglama courses, marbling art or mosque events to give them a cultural identity. Social ties are strengthened through activities such as holiday celebrations, family visits and iftar meals.</li>



<li><strong>Modern Events:</strong> Modern activities such as sports, art and science workshops develop children&#8217;s teamwork, creativity and problem-solving skills. Families encourage their children to participate in these activities according to their interests.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="a-bridge-between-the-past-and-the-future">A Bridge Between the Past and the Future</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey&#8217;s birth and child-rearing traditions are a reflection of its cultural richness. Family structure, social norms and traditions play an important role in the development of children. The traditions and methods discussed in this paper reflect Turkey&#8217;s rich cultural heritage. The process from birth to child rearing is shaped by the shared values of families and society. Understanding these traditions in Turkey is of great importance both as a cultural enrichment and for the integration of individuals into society. Remember, although each family differs with its own dynamics, love and support are always at the forefront.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>


<h3 class="wp-block-heading">What are the most common traditions after birth in Turkey?</h3>


<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The most common postpartum traditions in Turkey include baby mevlidi and maternity sherbet. These traditions are meant to celebrate the new member of the family and support the mother&#8217;s health.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="what-are-the-methods-of-raising-children-in-turkey">What are the methods of raising children in Turkey?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Child-rearing methods in Turkey include a combination of traditional and modern approaches. While teaching their children moral values, parents also give importance to academic success.</p>


<h3 class="wp-block-heading">How is the family structure in Turkey?</h3>


<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The extended family structure is common in Turkey. Children grow up with parents, grandparents and other relatives. This helps children develop social skills.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="why-parental-relationship-is-important-in-child-development">Why parental relationship is important in child development?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The parental relationship has a major impact on children&#8217;s emotional development and social skills. Open communication and a supportive environment contribute to the healthy growth of children.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="what-are-the-modern-methods-of-raising-children-in-turkey">What are the modern methods of raising children in Turkey?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Modern methods of raising children in Turkey include private schools, alternative education methods and social activities. These methods help children acquire different skills.</p>', "wp_published_at" = '2026-02-02T08:46:49Z', "wp_modified_at" = '2026-03-15T18:39:14Z', "featured_image" = '{"provider":"external","src":"/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/birth-and-child-raising-traditions-in-turkiye.webp","alt":"Turkish child with traditional bracelet","title":"birth-and-child-raising-traditions-in-turkiye"}' WHERE "deleted_at" IS NULL AND "status" = 'published' AND "locale" = 'en' AND "slug" = 'birth-child-raising-traditions-in-turkey';
