<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="important-rituals-in-traditional-turkish-weddings">Important Rituals in Traditional Turkish Weddings</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkish weddings are full of rituals and traditions. These rituals, performed before and after the wedding, have a great meaning to reinforce the happiness of the couple and their families. Here are some important rituals in traditional Turkish weddings:</p>


<h3>Henna Night:</h3>
<p>This event for the bride takes place the day before the wedding. Entertainment is organized with traditional music and henna is burned on the bride and guests. The ceremony is full of emotional moments; before the henna is burned on the bride&#8217;s hand, manis are sung, laments are made, and the bride&#8217;s farewell is symbolically reenacted. The henna night is not only an entertainment, but also an intimate ceremony for the bride where she spends her last girl&#8217;s day with her family and friends.</p>
<h3>Getting the Bride:</h3>
<p>On the wedding day, the bride is taken from her home to the wedding venue. Various traditions and rituals are performed during this process. For example, a red ribbon is usually cut as the bride leaves the house, or wheat, money and water are sprinkled behind her; this is done for fertility and good luck. When the groom&#8217;s side arrives to pick up the bride in his carriage, the bride&#8217;s brother or a young male relative will ask for a tip (door money), creating a symbolic obstacle. After a fun bargain, the gate is opened and the bride is escorted out. These rituals add to the joy and memory of the wedding.</p>
<h3>Wedding:</h3>


<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkish weddings are usually grand and colorful celebrations. At the center of the wedding is the bride&#8217;s reception. The groom and his friends arrive in a convoy of cars to pick up the bride from her home. In front of the bride&#8217;s house, fun rituals such as cutting red ribbons and negotiating tips (door money) are performed. As the bride leaves the house, wheat, money or water is sprinkled behind her; this is a symbolic gesture to bring prosperity and good luck. Once at the wedding site, the wedding ceremony begins, followed by a celebration with food, music and dancing. At Turkish weddings, folk dances (e.g. horon, zeybek) are played and guests are entertained by live musical performances. The bride and groom waltz in front of the guests or perform a symbolic cake cutting.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">At the end of the wedding, the bride and groom are sent off to their new home. This is when jokes are made, such as tying cans or shoes to the back of the car. Turkish weddings blend both traditional and modern elements to create an unforgettable experience.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">These rituals create special moments not only for couples, but also for families and friends.</p>



